at|mitche: Play:  When declarer won the @DA, East played the Jack. 
Declarer should now cross to dummy with a club (safe, since East would need 11 cards in clubs and hearts for this to 
get ruffed) and finesse the @D10.  Why?|
pg| ***** 79 ***** |


at|  
Believe it or not, the odds are 2 to 1 that the finesse will work. 
If you want to see detailed reasoning, google    "restricted choice."
The basic idea is that if East has the @DQJ doubleton, he could play either one at random. 
They are both equals, so it doesn't matter which one he plays.|
pg| ***** 80 ***** |


nt||
at|mitche:  But when he plays the J, it is a forced play.  Putting it a different way, the odds are 50-50 that she 
would play the J from QJ and 100% that she would play the Jack from singleton Jack.  So that means the odds are 
2:1 that she started with the singleton J  vs   QJ       which makes the finesse right.|
pg| ***** 81 ***** |


at|
Especially given that East has known heart length, the finesse is really the best play.
If East has 6 hearts, there are 7 unknown cards in her hand, and West has 3 hearts, hence 10 unknown cards in his. 
So the odds favor the @DQ to be with West either way you analyze the  hand.|
pg| ***** 82 ***** |


nt||
at|mitche:  Restricted choice extends to other situations, too, not just finessing against a Queen or Jack. 
Ken Lebensohl wrote a column many years ago, called "odd bridge" that has a restricted choice problem with odds of near
9 to 1.  Most importantly, it applies in situations where someone leads small from 4 or 5 in a suit and an honor 
shows up in third hand.  
Bridge logic says that the opening leader will have any honor lower in rank than the one third hand plays, but higher 
cards are easy to locate if you apply restricted choice to the distribution of the remaining honors higher 
than the one shown by third hand.|
